That's right, it's the smallest one. That site was served by a single threaded 
			32-bit Debian build.

*The API relies on a few C++11 features with fallbacks using the boost libraries.




Online monitoring made easy

Below you see the resource usage of this xenomat amidst other processes on your machine.
			Loading...
			//		


If you reboot the xenomat,
	             you might notice it getting a new PID, or shortly using 100% of the CPU, 
	             depending on your operating system.




History


		    Starting out as a private research project in 2004, it evolved to a full blown product for building HATEOAS applications in 2009 (you can tell from the so-last-decade styling here), and eventually matured into the present full stack reactive realtime processing platform during early 2014.




	            Over the years, netropy often has been used as an agile prototyping tool (e.g. configured to serve mock SOAP replies while finishing the frontend, instead of waiting for the other team to actually get their bloated J2EE system working).




	            It has also proven itself as a fun and easy way for hacking IoT stuff with the Raspberry Pi, and is steadily fulfilling its purpose as the foundation of a mission critical system for controlling rod pumping systems.



	            netropy marvels as a platform for microservices, makes a great IoT backend, 
	            and is a kind of Swiss army knife for bringing your legacy data wherever you need it.





Getting started


	            Please take a few minutes to get an overview of the concepts covered by this software:




	              A guided introduction (work in progress).



	              Basic Concepts



	              Structuring Information



	              Built In Services



Then, simply fetch the server binary, get a blueprint, and run:

# curl -O http://netropy.huebel.freeshells.org:8901/distribution/debian/xenomat
# chmod a+x xenomat
# curl -O http://netropy.huebel.freeshells.org:8901/download/blueprint.xml
# ./xenomat -d


		          The -d flag will make the server run in debug (console) mode. 
		          Running xenomat -h will display the command line syntax.





Demos



                Hello World

The mandatory minimal application.

Note the importance of the trailing slash on the url - it gives you a different context (the page can't resolve the stylesheet given by a relative link).



                Blueprint Navigator

Get a graphical overview over this <xeno:space/>.

XENOmat has full introspection, which lets you easily visualise your system with standard web components, such as letting the browser apply XSLT transformations.

A plain XML version (the actual source file) can be viewed here.



                Content Editor

A small AJAX application for modifying this 
                  <xeno:space/>. From long time before anything like jsfiddle and gists and cloud snippets existed. Useful for fast prototyping a backend. Of course you can use curl as well with any <xeno:stash/>.




                Sample SQL application

Using the <xeno:sql/> service to retrieve data from an Access database and letting the browser XSL‑Transform the resulting XML to XHTML.

Currently only working on Windows hosts, as the Linux/Darwin ports of the service (covering sqlite3, postgres, and mysql) are not completed. The jury is still out on which strategy to choose.

Anyway, you might have a look at the source to see how netropy connects to SQL.



                Escapa!

As above, this is not working - even the javascript seems not to run on modern browsers.

A fast paced javascript game with a running highscore stored in an Excel spreadsheet.

Current highscore: None so far...

Again you might have a look at the source to see how you can build applications with netropy.




				  Clock

A pure CSS animated SVG clock. No javascript needed.






Source and example code

Much of netropy is open source, licensed under the Netropy No Bullshit Licence (N2BL), which is basically a liberal BSD-style license.

The C++ API and examples are starting to show up on github.




















